My friend, the late Dr. Hopkins, thinks that this sentence of Sallust, Sin captus pravis cupidinib. &c., is easily re- ducible to reason and rule by altering the punctuation thus, Sin, cap- tus pravis cupidinibus, ad inertiam et voluptates corporis pessum da- tus est, perniciosa lubidine paulisper usus3 that is to say, If captivated by depraved desines, it is sunk in indolence and sensuality, in conse- quence of having for a short while given way to those desires, or that perniciosa lubinine. Here there is no hiatus, for all the rest reads smoothly, and in due connexion. Thus far the acute doctor. By hiatus the doctor meant, Ι presume, inconsequence, or inconnexion.
